PARAGRAPH.#text: Sprint shareholders want to like Marcelo Claure, the company's new chief executive.He gave them plenty of reason while speaking at a Goldman Sachs media and telecom conference Thursday. Mr. Claure, who has never run a public company and has been on the job for just weeks, said he was advised not to make changes within his first hundred days. "But I couldn't help myself," he said, explaining how he changed Sprint's pricing structure a mere four days after starting.Mr. Claure began by asking why anyone would want to buy a Sprint phone, noting that his company's prices were higher than peers' and its plans were confusing. "We were advertising a plan called 'Framily' that I had a hard time understanding," he said. Sprint's marketing for the plan was confusing, too: "It's a hamster talking to people," Mr. Claure added.That line drew laughs. But it is easy enough for Mr. Claure, whose company's stock has fallen nearly 40% this year, to come off as confident when talking about breaking from the past. The harder part is doing it.

Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Retailers Reel as Shoppers Shun Stores

PARAGRAPH.#text: Retailers are fighting a losing battle to get shoppers into their stores. A long-term change in consumer habits has reduced store traffic—perhaps permanently—and shifted pricing power away from malls and big-box retailers, write the WSJ's Shelly Banjo and Drew Fitzgerald. Online sales grew this holiday season at more than double the rate of brick-and-mortar sales. Shoppers don't seem to be using physical stores to browse as much, either. Instead, they seem to be figuring out what they want online, then making targeted trips to pick it up from retailers that offer the best price, Banjo and Fitzgerald say. Retailers think the traffic declines are likely to persist well past the holidays. "The reality is, we just don't see that changing," said Urban Outfitters CFO Frank Conforti.

Headlines.Headline: The Morning Download: Intel Sees 'Infinite Demand' for Smarter Things

PARAGRAPH.#text: Good morning. Since Intel CFO Stacy Smith started with the company 25 years ago he has seen the PC die "half a dozen times." After each previous death, it has come back as something else—a tower, a pizza box, etc. This time, the process of reincarnation is more complex, with mobile computing and other devices redefining computing. Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Consumers Splash Out on Big Ticket Items

PARAGRAPH.#text: We're seeing more evidence that U.S. consumers are splashing out on big ticket items. Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Banks Change Tune on Corporate Cash
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Banks Change Tune on Corporate Cash

PARAGRAPH.#text: Banks are changing their tune on corporate cash. After years of discouraging deposits, banks are making a big effort to attract them, writes CFOJ's Vipal Monga in today's Marketplace section. Looming regulatory changes, which will force banks to hold larger cash reserves, are driving the strategic shift. "Last year, almost every bank had more cash than they knew what to do with," Terry Stack, treasurer at Harman International Industries, tells Monga. "They were being decidedly stingy with the yields they were offering." But now companies are funneling their cash back into U.S. banks, which are offering them a new selection of products designed to appeal to corporate customers and average annual rates of 0.30% on deposits, up from 0.20% last year.
